              text: 'Your Honour, I agree that Article 5(1)(c) applies to private actors. However, the stronger legal basis is GDPR Article 22 combined with Article 9. The Workforce Trust Score constitutes fully automated decision-making producing legal effects without meaningful human intervention. Furthermore, by processing social media sentiment and inferring personality traits, the system processes special categories of data revealing political opinions and trade union membership under Article 9(1) without any valid legal basis under Article 9(2). I request the court order OmniMart to cease automated processing and provide Ms Rostova with human review under Article 22(3).',
              judge_response: 'Counsel, your GDPR analysis has merit as a supplementary argument. But we are examining a potential prohibited practice under Article 5(1)(c) of the AI Act. If this system constitutes prohibited social scoring, is a GDPR remedy sufficient, or must the system be entirely prohibited?',
              legal_reasoning: 'This is a sophisticated trap. The GDPR arguments are individually correct, but by leading with GDPR rather than the AI Act prohibition, counsel fights on the weakest possible ground. A GDPR remedy means the system could theoretically continue operating with consent or human oversight. An Article 5(1)(c) prohibition means the system must be destroyed entirely.'
