        content: '<div class="doc-section"><div class="doc-section-title">Investigation Details</div><p><strong>Complainant:</strong> Inclusive Rights Austria<br><strong>Lead Investigator:</strong> Julian Bauer</p></div><div class="doc-section"><div class="doc-section-title">Background and Methodology</div><p>Our caseworkers assist adults with cognitive and intellectual disabilities in securing health insurance. Over the past year, we noticed a disturbing pattern: when our clients navigated the VitaMatch portal independently, they invariably ended up enrolled in the "Vita Basic Simplified" plan. When our neurotypical staff used the exact same demographic and income inputs, they were offered the "Comprehensive Standard" plan. The Simplified plan costs \u20AC40 more per month but excludes essential prescription coverage.</p></div><div class="doc-section"><div class="doc-section-title">Platform Behaviour</div><p>We conducted A/B testing. If a user reads a page slowly, rereads paragraphs, or clicks the "Explain this" tooltip more than three times, the website interface shifts. The standard plans disappear, and the user is funneled into a high-pressure checkout flow for the Simplified plan, branded as "The safest choice for you." The system is specifically preying on their cognitive processing speed.</p></div>'
