    verdict: {
      winText: 'The Austrian Financial Market Authority finds that VitaMatch violated Article 5(1)(b) of Regulation (EU) 2024/1689. The FlowOptimizer system is a prohibited AI practice. It infers cognitive vulnerabilities through behavioural proxies and exploits those vulnerabilities to materially distort users\' economic behaviour, causing significant financial and health-related harm by steering them into predatory insurance plans. The prohibition under Title II is absolute and cannot be circumvented by claims of UX optimization, nor can it be legalized via GDPR consent or high-risk reclassification. VitaMatch is ordered to immediately cease deployment of the CLI routing logic and faces maximum administrative penalties.',
      loseText: 'The Authority finds your arguments insufficient to prove a violation of Article 5(1)(b). You failed to successfully articulate how inferring behavioural friction equates to exploiting a disability, or you failed to overcome the respondent\'s defense that obtaining GDPR consent for data processing resolves the legal conflict. VitaMatch\'s practices will be reviewed under standard consumer protection rules, but the AI Act prohibition claim is dismissed.',
      modelAnswer: 'A complete legal analysis must establish that the FlowOptimizer violates the absolute prohibition in Article 5(1)(b) of the EU AI Act. First, it must address the "proxy" issue: the AI Act does not require explicit medical data. Training a system to infer cognitive impairment via behavioural telemetry (the Cognitive Load Index) and targeting those users satisfies the element of exploiting a vulnerability due to a disability. Second, it must prove material distortion and significant harm: the AI deliberately suppresses standard options to isolate vulnerable users into "Simplified Plans," directly causing a severe financial penalty (\u20AC480/year) and a dangerous reduction in health coverage. Finally, the argument must assert the structural supremacy of Article 5: because the exploitation of vulnerabilities is an unacceptable risk, it is absolutely prohibited. It cannot be defended as "UX optimization," downgraded to a high-risk system, or legalized through GDPR consent banners. The only lawful remedy is immediate cessation.'
    }
