        date: 'October 10, 2025',
        content: '<div class="doc-section"><div class="doc-section-title">Field Observations - Operations</div><p>During the 72-hour window of Operation Sentinel, GPW field investigators closely monitored the deployment of the \'Aegis-X\' system at Central Station. Our experts noted that cameras were active in all public areas, without any physical or digital demarcation warning the public. This aggressive surveillance extended deep into high-privacy zones, including retail shops, family waiting areas, and the corridors directly leading into public restrooms within the station.</p></div><div class="doc-section"><div class="doc-section-title">Civilian Impact & Data Retention</div><p>Despite the massive scale of the operation, absolutely no signage was posted to inform the estimated 250,000 travellers passing through the transit hub that real-time remote biometric processing was underway. Citizens were entirely unaware their faces were being actively mapped and checked against watchlists. The targeted suspect, "The Architect", was never found during this period. Yet, we have verified that the <div class="doc-highlight">biometric data of all travellers was stored for 48 hours</div> post-operation for "further analysis." Retaining innocent people\'s biometric templates for two days completely violates the strict necessity constraints of the AI Act.</p></div>'
