        date: 'October 3, 2025',
        content: '<div class="doc-section"><div class="doc-section-title">Document Metadata</div><p><strong>Reference:</strong> FRIA-2024-Retail-Amended<br><strong>System:</strong> Aegis-X Facial Recognition<br><strong>Authorising Officer:</strong> Comm. Vance</p></div><div class="doc-section"><div class="doc-section-title">Impact Assessment (Abridged)</div><p><strong>1. Fundamental Rights Considered:</strong> The primary right impacted is Privacy (High Risk). Freedom of assembly and movement are considered secondary impacts during the operational window.</p><p><strong>2. Proportionality & Mitigation:</strong> To mitigate privacy intrusions, all intercepted biometric data will be encrypted at rest and in transit. The necessity of this deployment is classified as \'High\' due to the immediate terrorism threat posed by the suspect.</p><p><strong>3. Risk Analysis:</strong> The system has been tested for accuracy in controlled environments. However, <div class="doc-highlight">the assessment does not include specific impacts on vulnerable groups or the risk of false positives</div> in a high-density transit environment like a central railway station. Furthermore, there is no analysis regarding the algorithmic bias across different demographics, nor does it address the psychological chilling effect on the general public commuting through the station.</p></div>'
