    verdict: {
      winText: 'Victory! The Tribunal has ordered the immediate decommissioning of the ClearSight AI database. Justice Rossi ruled that the company\'s business model is a textbook example of a prohibited practice under Article 5(1)(e). The court found that \"untargeted scraping\" refers to the indiscriminate method of collection, which the company admitted to in its own technical documents and marketing. The \"Legacy Database\" defense was rejected, with the court ruling that the ongoing \"placing on the market\" and \"use\" of the system constitutes a continuous violation of the AI Act. ClearSight must now certify the permanent deletion of all 20 billion records.',
      loseText: 'Defeat. The Court found that while the company\'s practices were \"concerning,\" your legal team failed to effectively counter the respondent\'s claim that their scraping was \"purposeful\" and therefore \"targeted.\" Because you focused on the privacy of the journalist rather than the technical \"untargeted\" ingestion process defined in Article 5(1)(e), the court has allowed ClearSight to continue operating while they seek a high-risk conformity assessment.',
      modelAnswer: 'ClearSight AI is in violation of Article 5(1)(e) of the EU AI Act, which prohibits the placing on the market or use of AI systems that create or expand facial recognition databases through the untargeted scraping of facial images from the internet or CCTV footage. The system fails the legal test on three counts: 1) The scraping methodology (Evidence 2 and 4) is untargeted and indiscriminate, ingesting all available facial data; 2) The sources used (Internet and Live City Cams) are explicitly covered by the prohibition; and 3) The ongoing \"placing on the market\" of the database (Evidence 6) makes the violation current and actionable, regardless of when the initial scraping occurred. ClearSight\'s internal awareness of this violation (Evidence 5) further supports the need for an immediate cessation of the prohibited practice rather than a high-risk compliance pathway.'
    }
