              text: 'Your Honour, the police are just using the human as a rubber stamp. The witness said they stop anyone with a high score, so the human isn\'t really thinking for themselves. This is exactly what the AI Act is trying to stop: computers making decisions about who is a criminal and who isn\'t. If the police can\'t find a real reason to stop my client, they shouldn\'t be allowed to use a computer to give them a fake reason. The \"support tool\" excuse is just a way to hide the truth.',
              judge_response: 'I agree that the "rubber stamp" is a concern, but you must explain why this fails the specific legal test in Article 5(1)(d). What is the definition of "support" in the Act?',
              legal_reasoning: 'Correct in spirit but lacks statutory precision. It fails to cite the specific "objective and verifiable facts" requirement of the Art 5(1)(d) exception.'
