              text: 'Your Honour, the high rate of flags for innocent individuals is a violation of the \"Accuracy and Robustness\" requirements in Article 15. The AI Act requires that high-risk systems be designed to achieve an appropriate level of accuracy throughout their lifecycle. A system that is wrong 85% of the time is clearly not fit for purpose and has a high rate of false positives. The remedy is for the court to order the NRPF to recalibrate the algorithm and submit it for a new bias audit to ensure it doesn\'t unfairly target people from poor neighbourhoods.',
              judge_response: 'Counsel, you are once again proposing a \"recalibration\" of a practice that appears to be prohibited. If the system\'s logic is based on prohibited profiling, does it matter if it is 15% accurate or 90% accurate?',
              legal_reasoning: 'This is the trap. It suggests that the problem is the *accuracy* (Art 15) rather than the *nature* of the system (Art 5). If a practice is prohibited, its level of accuracy or recalibration is irrelevant to its legality.'
