    verdict: {
      winText: 'Victory! The Tribunal has ordered the immediate shutdown of Prism-AI. Justice Vossen ruled that the system is a prohibited practice under Article 5(1)(g), confirming that biometric categorisation for the purpose of inferring ethnicity, religion, or political leanings is an absolute violation of the AI Act. The court rejected the \"anonymity\" defense, ruling that \"categorizing individually natural persons\" applies to the processing of any single person, regardless of whether their legal name is known. Aura Analytics must now delete all segment logs and pay a significant fine.',
      loseText: 'Defeat. The Court found that while the company\'s practices were \"intrusive,\" your legal team failed to effectively argue why the system didn\'t fall under the high-risk category for marketing. Because you focused on the \"anonymity\" of the shoppers rather than the specific statutory prohibition on \"inferring protected traits,\" the court has allowed Aura Analytics to continue using the system as long as they provide a QR code for an \"opt-out.\"',
      modelAnswer: 'Aura Analytics\' Prism-AI system is a prohibited practice under Article 5(1)(g) of the EU AI Act. This provision prohibits biometric categorisation systems that categorise individually natural persons based on their biometric data to deduce or infer protected characteristics, including race, political opinions, and religious beliefs. The system fails the legal test on three grounds: 1) It uses biometric data (facial and vocal landmarks) to perform the categorisation (Evidence 2); 2) The categories it infers (Race, Politics, Religion) are explicitly prohibited (Evidence 5); and 3) The respondent\'s \"anonymity\" and \"probability\" defenses are semantically hollow, as the law protects natural persons from being individually categorised regardless of identification (Recital 44). The exception for \"labelling and filtering\" is inapplicable here, as it is strictly limited to law enforcement, migration, and asylum contexts.'
    }
