              quality: 'strong',
              text: 'Your Honour, the respondent\'s argument ignores the explicit duty in Article 14(4)(b) to ensure that users are aware of and can remain aware of the tendency of \'automation bias.\' The statistics (Evidence 4) show a dangerous collapse in independent clinical judgment, where the override rate dropped to 1.8% while false negatives tripled. The witness testimony (Evidence 5) confirms that this is not trust, but surrender to administrative friction. A system designed to make disagreement more difficult than agreement facilitates automation bias rather than minimizing it, violating the core safety purpose of Article 14.',
              judge_response: 'The tripling of false negatives alongside the drop in overrides is a critical correlation. It suggests that the \"trust\" mentioned by the provider is actually an inability to intervene.',
