              id: 'arg3-strong',
              quality: 'strong',
              text: 'Your Honour, the respondent is attempting to use contracts to bypass statutory safety requirements. Article 9(2) of the AI Act requires that risk management measures be implemented through technical design and development. Designating a system as \'Assistant Only\' in a manual (Evidence 6) is a purely procedural mitigation that does nothing to address the structural automation bias built into the software\'s interface. When a known risk—automation bias—is identified, the provider has a legal duty to minimize it through the system\'s design, not simply to shift the legal liability to the user through a service agreement.',
              judge_response: 'Contracts cannot override the safety obligations of the AI Act. If the design creates the risk, the design must mitigate it. Procedural warnings are the last resort, not the first step in risk management.',
