    verdict: {
      winText: 'Victory! The Court has ruled that MediLogic Systems is liable for a breach of the AI Act. Justice Morel found that TriageFlow AI failed to meet the mandatory human oversight requirements of Article 14. The court ruled that the \"justification modal\" and \"lockout timer\" were technical barriers that effectively prevented doctors from overriding the system, thereby nullifying the human-in-the-loop requirement. The provider was also found to have failed its risk management duties under Article 9 by relying on procedural warnings instead of safe design to mitigate automation bias.',
      loseText: 'Defeat. The Court found that while the software design was \"unfortunate,\" the final clinical responsibility remained with Dr. Aris. Because you failed to effectively link the UI design to the specific statutory duty in Article 14 to *enable* oversight, the court ruled that the doctor\'s failure to override the system was an independent act of negligence, shielding the AI provider from liability.',
      modelAnswer: 'MediLogic Systems violated the EU AI Act on two primary counts. First, the system\'s design violated Article 14 (Human Oversight). Under Art. 14(4), oversight measures must enable users to disregard or override AI output. The \"Justification Modal\" and 30-second lockout timer (Evidence 2) created undue administrative friction that discouraged intervention, a failure reflected in the collapse of override rates (Evidence 4). Second, the provider breached Article 9 (Risk Management). Art. 9(2) requires that risks be mitigated primarily through design and development. MediLogic identified automation bias but chose a procedural mitigation (\'Assistant Only\' label in a manual) rather than a technical design that minimized the bias, which is a violation of the mandatory risk management hierarchy. By designing a system that made disagreement more costly than agreement, the provider created a structural failure of human oversight.'
    }

