              text: 'Your Honour, the university has violated the \"Quality Management System\" rules in Article 17. A high-risk system must have a QMS that includes procedures for data governance and post-market monitoring. Because the university didn\'t have a specific policy for neurodivergent students, their QMS was defective. The remedy is to fine the university under Article 99 and order them to hire a Disability Compliance Officer to review the AI logs. This will bring the school into compliance with the administrative requirements of the AI Act while allowing the system to continue operating.',
              judge_response: 'Counsel, you are proposing a procedural fix for a substantive violation of fundamental rights. If the system is biased and lacks oversight, does hiring an officer fix the legality of Malik\'s expulsion?',
              legal_reasoning: 'This is the trap. It suggests a procedural remedy (Art 17 QMS, Art 99 fines) instead of addressing the core safety and rights violation. It seeks to \"fix the paperwork\" rather than overturn the discriminatory decision.'
