    verdict: {
      winText: 'Victory! The Court has ordered St. Jude\'s University to reinstate Malik Jones and void his failure. Justice Vossen ruled that the university violated Article 10(3) by using a system with non-representative training data and Article 14 by implementing an \"automatic failure\" policy that turned human oversight into a procedural sham. The court noted that the university\'s failure to mitigate known risks to neurodivergent students, despite being warned by their own tech lead, was a clear breach of the risk management duties in Article 9.',
      loseText: 'Defeat. The Court found that while the bias in the system was concerning, your legal team failed to effectively prove that the university\'s oversight was legally \"ineffective.\" Because you focused on the \"unfairness\" of the expulsion rather than the specific statutory requirements for representative training data in Article 10, the court has allowed the university to continue using the system as long as they offer a human-led appeal process.',
      modelAnswer: 'The University violated the EU AI Act on three primary counts. First, the training data for the high-risk proctoring system (Annex III, 3b) failed the Article 10(3) representativeness test; a 95% Caucasian dataset is statistically inappropriate for a diverse population and leads to biased outcomes (Evidence 4). Second, the University failed its human oversight obligations under Article 14. By implementing an \"automatic failure\" policy (Evidence 3) and allowing a rubber-stamp review process (Evidence 5), they failed to minimize automation bias or enable the human to effectively disregard the AI output. Finally, the University breached Article 9 by failing to implement technical mitigations for a known risk to neurodivergent students identified before deployment (Evidence 6). High-risk systems must be safe and non-discriminatory for their entire intended population; aggregate efficiency does not excuse systemic bias.'
    }
