            text: 'Your Honour, Article 10(2)(f) explicitly mandates that high-risk AI training data be examined for possible biases that have a negative impact on fundamental rights. The technical logs (Evidence 2) reveal a dataset where 65% of records come from 15% of the population, reflecting decades of disproportionate policing. Simply labeling these historical patterns as \'facts\' does not discharge the provider\'s duty to mitigate bias. By training the AI on un-detoxified data, the respondent has automated a cycle of discrimination, violating the mandatory requirement to ensure datasets are relevant and representative of the intended population without perpetuating historical exclusion.',
            judge_response: 'The court agrees. \"Historical fact\" is often the source of prohibited bias under the AI Act. If the data is skewed by over-policing, it is not \"sufficiently representative\" as required by Article 10(3).',
