      content: '<div class="doc-section"><div class="doc-section-title">Q2 2025 Judicial Performance Review</div><p><strong>Prepared by:</strong> Ministry of Justice Analytics Division</p></div><div class="doc-section"><table class="doc-table"><tr><th>Metric</th><th>Pre-AI (2023)</th><th>Post-AI (Q2 2025)</th><th>Variance</th></tr><tr><td>Sentences matching algorithmic baseline</td><td>N/A</td><td><div class="doc-highlight">94.2%</div></td><td>High Adherence</td></tr><tr><td>Sentencing variance for similar crimes</td><td>32.5%</td><td>4.1%</td><td>-87% (Standardization)</td></tr><tr><td>Prosecution appeals for \'inconsistency\'</td><td>Baseline</td><td>+400%</td><td>Targeted against human deviations</td></tr></table></div><div class="doc-section"><div class="doc-section-title">Impact on Judicial Discretion</div><p>Since the mandatory launch of Veritas-Judge, <div class="doc-highlight">94% of all sentences have fallen exactly within the AI\'s suggested range.</div> The administrative friction of the "Reasoning Form" and the threat of the compliance audit have virtually eliminated individual judicial discretion. Furthermore, the prosecution division is systematically using the AI score as the baseline for appeals, successfully overturning 88% of cases where a human judge attempted to grant leniency below the AI\'s recommendation.</p></div>'
