  verdict: {
    winText: 'Victory! The Supreme Court of Appeal has ruled that the sentencing process was unlawful. Justice Rossi found that the Ministry of Justice violated Article 14 of the AI Act by creating an administrative environment that rendered human oversight ineffective. The court ruled that \"AI Compliance Rates\" and \"Retraining\" threats for deviations constitute a structural failure to minimize automation bias. The court has ordered that Thomas Miller be re-sentenced by a human judge with no reference to the AI score, and the Ministry has been ordered to dismantle the adherence-tracking dashboard.',
    loseText: 'Defeat. The Court found that while the Ministry\'s metrics were \"concerning,\" the final signature on the sentence was still human. Because you failed to effectively prove that professional pressure constitutes a technical failure of \"effective oversight\" under Article 14, the court has ruled that the judge\'s decision to follow the AI was a valid exercise of his discretion, shielding the Ministry from liability.',
    modelAnswer: 'The Ministry of Justice violated the EU AI Act on two primary counts. First, Veritas-Judge failed the Article 14(1) and (4) human oversight mandate. High-risk systems must be designed to allow effective oversight, which includes the ability to disregard or override the output (Art 14(4e)). By tracking \"AI Compliance Rates\" (Evidence 3) and subjecting judges who deviate to performance audits (Evidence 5), the Ministry created a structural environment that obstructed the exercise of this discretion. Second, the system failed to address \"automation bias\" as required by Art 14(4b). The 94% adherence rate (Evidence 4) is evidence not of accuracy, but of a design that compels over-reliance through professional coercion. Institutional efficiency and \"sentencing consistency\" cannot override the mandatory requirement for meaningful human agency in high-risk judicial assessments.'
  }
